node.text:
Weekend bread baking: 4x900g loaves made with 40% @carolinaground whole wheat topped with instant oats. These sumptuous loaves are satisfying all the bread-eating this weekend and into this coming week. The interior is quite tender, contrasted by a satisfying thick crust. Ever eat bread you swear has inclusions mixed in because of all the flavors that pop? These are those.

60% @giustos1940 artisan baker's craft
40% @carolinaground  whole wheat (so good!)
80% water
1.8% salt
17.38% ripe levain (100% whole wheat, 100% water, 50% sourdough starter @ 5 hours)
75F (23C) final dough temp
3-hour bulk
12-hour retard

node.text: Sourdough apple + blueberry crostata (aka galette) with the first gravenstein apples from my trees! The recipe for the dough is at the link in my profile, I subbed out 30g of the white flour for buckwheat, just for fun. Tonight we’re doing a “campout” in the yard with the kiddos and this galette is on the menu 😀 Will post more in my Stories. Happy Wednesday, everyone ⚡️

node.text: A little weekend sourdough pizza—not bad, could be a lot better. Did I enjoy it? Absolutely! I tried using Caputo flour for the first time in a long time (thanks for all the info, @bartfeldbread!). The dough was a little over-proofed (this the scorching on the larger bubbles forming, kissing the flames curling above), but it’ll be fun to play more in the coming weeks. The cheese also was not a good choice (notice how even though it’s in small pieces, it refused to melt), will be seeking out another option. Even with all my picky, still tasty and I ate the whole thing 😅 #pizza #sourdough #naturallyleavened

node.text: Sourdough English muffin test number I-lost-count. Most promising results so far, but still working on dialing in the process and texture. With these, I find the process for cooking/baking is just as important as the dough formula. How do you like to eat your muffin? Planning for a bacon + egg + mayo bunch here in a few! #sourdough #baking #englishmuffin

node.text: My sourdough baps recipe is ready for all the summer grilling days! My latest for @food52 is a recipe for these naturally leavened baps, a.k.a. 🍔 buns out this way. It just so happens these are also #vegan: there's no dairy of any kind, and yet these are super tender and sturdy enough to hang on to all manner of condiments. Head to the link in my profile for the recipe—enjoy! ⚡️

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by The Perfect Loaf in Albuquerque, New Mexico. May be an image of bread.

node.text: Seeded spelt sourdough! Added in a mix of 6% flax+sesame to this dough along with 30% whole grain @carolinaground spelt and 8% whole grain rye. Topped in raw wheat bran. Awesome aroma in the kitchen this afternoon. #sourdough #bread #bakingfromscratch

node.text: Early morning Sunday sourdough pancakes. Worth getting up a little early for, especially since I can sneak a few before everyone else stirs 😅 #sourdough #breakfast #weekend

node.text: Yesterday’s sourdough pizza for Italy’s big game (and the win! ⚽️ 🎉). Swipe on for bonus video of my dad shaping out pizza his way—seasoned hands shaping pizza for many, many years. This was a two day dough, retarded in bulk, balled up in the morning, cooked after about 4 hours at room temp.

node.text:
🍞 New recipe (link below and in profile)! I'd probably classify many of my sourdough bread recipes as "no-knead" since I often opt for skipping any dough development upfront (including slap/fold). Instead, I rely on stretches and folds during bulk fermentation—it's always surprising at just how much strength a dough can gain with a few simple folds. However, my new recipe explicitly calls this out and makes for a super easy couple of loaves of sourdough bread, a great place to start baking sourdough if you've been intimidated by the process!

Have fun and happy baking, everyone 🙂
https://www.theperfectloaf.com/easy-no-knead-sourdough-bread/

Ciabattine⚡️! My latest recipe for @food52 is for these small ciabatta rolls (recipe in profile and linked below!). The dough is all hand-mixed and done over two days, making for a straightforward dough to handle. There's essentially no preshaping or shaping, either; it's just cut, proofed, and baked—the perfect "hands-off" dough for lazy summers and perfect for summer sandwiches. For me, this recipe is going to be on repeat through the entirety of tomato season; there's little better than ciabatta with tomato, mozzarella, a little OO, and balsamic vinegar. 

https://food52.com/recipes/85964-sourdough-ciabatta-rolls-recipe
